## Build a Notification Badge in Angular

**Mental Model:** We'll create a simple Angular component that displays a bell icon and an overlaid badge showing an unread count. The key is using relative positioning for the badge to sit on top of the bell, and conditional rendering to hide the badge when there are no unread notifications.

### Step 1 — Set up the Component Structure
We'll define an `AppComponent` with an inline template. The template will contain a container for the bell and badge, using `position: relative` on the container and `position: absolute` on the badge to overlay it correctly.

```html
<div style="position: relative; display: inline-block;">
  <!-- Bell icon placeholder -->
  🔔
  <!-- Badge will go here -->
</div>
```

### Step 2 — Implement the Badge Display Logic
The badge will display the `unreadCount` if it's greater than zero. We'll use `*ngIf` to conditionally render the badge and `[innerText]` to display the count. We'll also add basic inline styling for the badge's appearance.

```html
<div style="position: relative; display: inline-block; font-size: 2em;">
  🔔
  <span
    *ngIf="unreadCount > 0"
    [innerText]="unreadCount"
    style="
      position: absolute;
      top: 0px;
      right: 0px;
      background-color: red;
      color: white;
      border-radius: 50%;
      padding: 0.2em 0.5em;
      font-size: 0.5em;
      line-height: 1;
      text-align: center;
      transform: translate(50%, -50%);
      min-width: 1.5em;
      box-sizing: border-box;
    "
  ></span>
</div>
```

### Step 3 — Add Interaction and Demo Controls
To demonstrate the badge, we'll add buttons to increment and decrement the `unreadCount`. This will show how the badge updates dynamically and hides when the count reaches zero.

```html
<div>
  <button (click)="increment()">Increment</button>
  <button (click)="decrement()">Decrement</button>
</div>
```

### Step 4 — Define Component Properties and Methods
In the `AppComponent` class, we'll define the `unreadCount` property and the `increment` and `decrement` methods. The `decrement` method will ensure the count doesn't go below zero.

```typescript
export class AppComponent {
  unreadCount: number = 0;

  increment(): void {
    this.unreadCount++;
  }

  decrement(): void {
    if (this.unreadCount > 0) {
      this.unreadCount--;
    }
  }
}
```

**Edge Cases:**

| Case                  | Handling                                        |
| :-------------------- | :---------------------------------------------- |
| `unreadCount` is 0    | Badge is hidden using `*ngIf`.                  |
| `unreadCount` is large | Badge `padding` and `min-width` ensure readability. |
| Negative `unreadCount` | `decrement()` method prevents count from going below 0. |

**Interview tip:** Be prepared to discuss accessibility (e.g., `aria-label` for the bell and badge), different ways to style (e.g., component styles vs. inline), and how to handle very large numbers (e.g., displaying "99+" instead of the exact count).

